{"id":"2009.14555","submitter":"Tim Wallis","authors":"Tim Wallis, Philip T. Barton, Nikolaos Nikiforakis","title":"A Diffuse Interface Model of Reactive-fluids and Solid-dynamics","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Computers & Structures, Volume 254, 2021","doi":"10.1016/j.compstruc.2021.106578","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.comp-ph physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  This article presents a multi-physics methodology for the numerical\nsimulation of physical systems that involve the non-linear interaction of\nmulti-phase reactive fluids and elastoplastic solids, inducing high\nstrain-rates and high deformations. Each state of matter is governed by a\nsingle system of non-linear, inhomogeneous partial differential equations,\nwhich are solved simultaneously on the same computational grid, and do not\nrequire special treatment of immersed boundaries. To this end, the governing\nequations for solid and reactive multiphase fluid mechanics are written in the\nsame mathematical form and are discretised on a regular Cartesian mesh. All\nphase and material boundaries are treated as diffuse interfaces. An\ninterface-steepening technique is employed at material boundaries to keep\ninterfaces sharp whilst maintaining the conservation properties of the system.\nThese algorithms are implemented in a highly-parallelised hierarchical adaptive\nmesh refinement platform, and are verified and validated using numerical and\nexperimental benchmarks. Results indicate very good agreement with experiment\nand an improvement of numerical performance compared to certain existing\nEulerian methods, without loss of conservation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 30 Sep 2020 10:53:08 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 21 May 2021 16:17:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-06-04"}
